section
  section
    h3 Twenty Questions
    p I choose a number from $1$ to $N$.
    p.fragment You ask yes/no questions.
    p.fragment Each answer gives one bit.
  section
    h3 Counting transcripts
    p $$q\text{ yes/no answers} \quad \Rightarrow \quad 2^q\text{ possible transcripts}.$$
    p.fragment With truthful answers, this is binary search.
    p.fragment.red What replaces it when answers may be lies?

section
  section
    h3 Ulam's one-lie game
    p Classical version:
    p How many yes/no questions are needed
    p to determine a number from $1$ to $10^6$
    p if one answer may be a lie?
  section
    h3 Why $20$ is not enough
    p $2^{20}=1{,}048{,}576$
    p.fragment Enough for truthful Twenty Questions.
    p.fragment But now one answer may be corrupted.
  section
    h3 One true transcript
    p With $q$ answers, one true transcript can become:
    ul
      li.fragment itself
      li.fragment the transcript with answer $1$ flipped
      li.fragment the transcript with answer $2$ flipped
      li.fragment $\dots$
      li.fragment the transcript with answer $q$ flipped
    p.fragment So one secret number occupies about $q+1$ possible transcripts.
  section
    h3 A coding bound
    p Therefore a necessary condition is
    p $$N(q+1)\le 2^q.$$
    p.fragment For $N=10^6$, this rules out $q=24$.
    p.fragment $25$ questions are enough.
  section
    h3 The lesson
    p Truthful Twenty Questions is binary search.
    p.fragment Ulam's liar game is error correction.
    p.fragment The answers form a word, and a lie is a bit error.

section
  section
    h3 IMO 2012 Problem 3
    p The official problem is called the liar's guessing game.
    p.fragment Proposed by David Arthur, Canada.
  section.statement
    h3 Original statement
    p The liar's guessing game is played between two players $A$ and $B$.
    p The rules depend on two fixed positive integers $k$ and $n$, known to both players.
  section.statement
    h3 Original statement
    p At the start, $A$ chooses integers $x$ and $N$ with $1\le x\le N$.
    p $A$ keeps $x$ secret, and truthfully tells $N$ to $B$.
  section.statement
    h3 Original statement
    p Player $B$ asks questions of the form:
    p.question Is $x\in S$?
    p where $S$ is an arbitrary set of positive integers.
    p.fragment The set $S$ may even be one used in a previous question.
  section.statement
    h3 Original statement
    p $B$ may ask as many questions as he wishes.
    p After each question, $A$ immediately answers yes or no.
    p.fragment $A$ may lie as many times as she wants.
    p.fragment.red But among any $k+1$ consecutive answers, at least one answer is truthful.
  section.statement
    h3 Original statement
    p At the end, $B$ specifies a set $X$ of at most $n$ positive integers.
    p If $x\in X$, then $B$ wins.
    p Otherwise, $B$ loses.
  section
    h3 Prove
    p.fragment (a) If $n\ge 2^k$, then $B$ can guarantee a win.
    p.fragment (b) For all sufficiently large $k$, there exists an integer
    p.fragment $$n\ge (1.99)^k$$
    p.fragment such that $B$ cannot guarantee a win.

section
  section
    h3 The coding view
    table.dictionary
      tbody
        tr
          th Guessing game
          th Coding theory
        tr.fragment
          td secret number $x$
          td message
        tr.fragment
          td answer history
          td received word
        tr.fragment
          td lie
          td bit error
        tr.fragment
          td final set $X$
          td decoded list
  section
    h3 The special error rule
    p Classical liar games often say:
    p $$\text{at most }e\text{ lies total}.$$
    p.fragment IMO 2012 P3 says instead:
    p.fragment $$\text{not }k+1\text{ lies in a row}.$$
    p.fragment Errors can happen many times, but not in one long block.

section
  section
    h3 Part (a)
    p Goal: if $n\ge 2^k$, Bob can force a final list of size at most $n$.
    p.fragment It is enough to force a list of size at most $2^k$.
  section
    h3 Key claim
    blockquote
      | If Bob has $2^k+1$ current candidates,
      br
      | then in at most $2k+1$ questions
      br
      | he can rule out at least one of them.
    p.fragment Then he repeats the claim until only $2^k$ candidates remain.
  section
    h3 Why relabeling is allowed
    p Bob knows $N$, so initially the candidates are
    p $$\{1,2,\dots,N\}.$$
    p.fragment If more than $2^k$ candidates remain, choose any $2^k+1$ of them.
    p.fragment Relabel those candidates
    p $$1,2,\dots,2^k,2^k+1.$$
    p.fragment Since Bob may ask about arbitrary sets $S$, this relabeling costs nothing.
  section
    h3 First question
    p Let
    p $$S_0=\{2^k+1\}.$$
    p Bob asks:
    p.question.fragment Is $x\in S_0$?
    p.fragment He repeats this until either Alice says yes,
    p.fragment or he has asked it $k+1$ times.
  section
    h3 If all answers are no
    p Suppose Alice answers no to $S_0$ for $k+1$ consecutive questions.
    p.fragment Among those $k+1$ answers, at least one is truthful.
    p.fragment So $x\notin S_0$.
    p.fragment.red Bob rules out $2^k+1$.
  section
    h3 If Alice says yes
    p Stop asking $S_0$ immediately.
    p.fragment Now use the other $2^k$ candidates:
    p $$T=\{1,2,\dots,2^k\}.$$
    p.fragment Think of each number in $T$ by its $k$ binary digits.
  section
    h3 Bit questions
    p For $i=1,\dots,k$, define
    p $$S_i=\{y\in T:\text{the }i\text{th least significant binary digit of }y\text{ is }1\}.$$
    p.fragment Bob asks:
    p.question.fragment Is $x\in S_i$?
    p.fragment for $i=1,2,\dots,k$.
  section
    h3 Example of the sets
    p For $k=3$, the candidates in $T$ are $1,\dots,8$.
    table.bits
      tbody
        tr
          th
          th $S_1$
          th $S_2$
          th $S_3$
        tr
          td meaning
          td last bit $1$
          td second bit $1$
          td third bit $1$
        tr
          td examples
          td $1,3,5,7$
          td $2,3,6,7$
          td $4,5,6,7$
  section
    h3 The opposite candidate
    p Alice has now given one yes to $S_0$ and $k$ answers to $S_1,\dots,S_k$.
    p.fragment There is a unique $y\in T$ whose binary digits make all $k$ bit answers false.
    table.bits.fragment
      tbody
        tr
          td Alice says
          td yes
          td no
          td no
          td yes
        tr
          td bit of $y$
          td 0
          td 1
          td 1
          td 0
  section
    h3 Why $y$ is ruled out
    p The answer yes to $S_0$ is false for $y$,
    p because $y\in T$ and $y\notin S_0$.
    p.fragment The next $k$ bit answers are also false for $y$ by construction.
    p.fragment If $x=y$, Alice has given $k+1$ consecutive lies.
    p.fragment.red Impossible.
  section
    h3 The claim is proved
    p Therefore $x\neq y$.
    p.fragment Bob has ruled out one candidate from the chosen block of $2^k+1$.
    p.fragment Repeating this leaves at most $2^k$ candidates.
    p.fragment Since $n\ge 2^k$, Bob wins.

section
  section
    h3 Part (b)
    p We show why Bob cannot hope for much less than $2^k$.
    p.fragment It is enough, for large $k$, to take
    p.fragment $$n=\lfloor 1.99^k\rfloor,\qquad N=n+1.$$
    p.fragment Alice will answer so that all $N$ original numbers remain possible.
  section
    h3 Bad sets
    p At question $t$, Bob asks about some set $S_t$.
    p.fragment Alice's answer can always be written as
    p $$x\notin B_t,$$
    p where $B_t$ is either $S_t$ or its complement.
    p.fragment Think of $B_t$ as the bad set for that answer.
  section
    h3 What kills a candidate?
    p For a candidate $x$, the answer at time $t$ is false exactly when
    p $$x\in B_t.$$
    p.fragment So $x$ is impossible only if it lies in $k+1$ consecutive bad sets:
    p $$x\in B_t\cap B_{t+1}\cap\dots\cap B_{t+k}.$$
  section
    h3 The quantity to control
    p After time $t$, let $e(x)$ be the current run length:
    p $$e(x)=\max\{e:x\in B_t\cap B_{t-1}\cap\dots\cap B_{t-e+1}\}.$$
    p.fragment Alice wants to keep every $e(x)\le k$.
  section
    h3 Weights
    p Give each candidate weight
    p $$w(x)=1.998^{e(x)}.$$
    p.fragment Large weight means the candidate is close to being killed.
    p.fragment Let
    p $$W=\sum_{x=1}^N w(x).$$
  section
    h3 Alice's rule
    p Bob asks about $S_t$.
    p.fragment Alice chooses $B_t$ to be whichever of $S_t$ or its complement has smaller total weight.
    p.fragment Thus the weight inside $B_t$ is at most $W/2$.
  section
    h3 Weight update
    p Candidates in $B_t$ extend their bad run:
    p $$w(x)\mapsto 1.998\,w(x).$$
    p.fragment Candidates outside $B_t$ reset:
    p $$w(x)\mapsto 1.$$
    p.fragment Therefore, except for the harmless empty-set case,
    p $$W_{\text{new}}\le 1.998\cdot {W\over2}+n=0.999W+n.$$
  section
    h3 The bound stays bounded
    p Initially
    p $$W_0=N=n+1<1000n.$$
    p.fragment If $W<1000n$, then
    p $$W_{\text{new}}<0.999(1000n)+n=1000n.$$
    p.fragment So Alice keeps $W<1000n$ forever.
  section
    h3 Why this prevents elimination
    p For large $k$,
    p $$1000n<1000(1.99^k+1)<1.998^{k+1}.$$
    p.fragment If some candidate had $e(x)=k+1$,
    p its weight alone would be $1.998^{k+1}$.
    p.fragment But total weight is smaller than that.
    p.fragment.red No candidate is ever ruled out.
  section
    h3 Bob's final list
    p Bob eventually names a set $X$ with at most $n$ integers.
    p.fragment But $N=n+1$, so some $x\in\{1,\dots,N\}$ is not in $X$.
    p.fragment Alice's answers are still consistent with this $x$:
    p.fragment in every $k+1$ consecutive answers, at least one answer is truthful.
    p.fragment Therefore Bob loses.
  section
    h3 Motivation for the weights
    p Think backwards from a forbidden run of length $k+1$.
    ul
      li.fragment At most two candidates can safely be at danger level $k$.
      li.fragment At most four candidates can be at danger level $k-1$.
      li.fragment At most eight candidates can be at danger level $k-2$.
    p.fragment This suggests weights like $2^e$.
  section
    h3 The small tilt
    p With exact weights $2^e$, the total danger can fail to decrease.
    p.fragment The proof uses
    p $$1.998^e$$
    p.fragment instead of $2^e$.
    p.fragment The extra room comes from proving only
    p $$n\ge 1.99^k,$$
    p.fragment not the stronger threshold $n\ge 2^k$.

section
  section
    h3 The story
    table.story
      tbody
        tr.fragment
          td Ordinary Twenty Questions
          td binary search
        tr.fragment
          td Ulam's one-lie game
          td error correction
        tr.fragment
          td Lies
          td bit errors
        tr.fragment
          td Final set $X$
          td decoded list
        tr.fragment
          td IMO 2012 P3
          td no long run of errors
  section
    h3 Closing
    p Part (a): Bob uses $k$ binary questions after one suspicious answer.
    p.fragment That is where $2^k$ appears.
    p.fragment Part (b): Alice spreads the danger with weights.
    p.fragment So Bob cannot force a list as small as $1.99^k$ for large $k$.
